commit.message:
Automate Wordpress steup

The entire project is focused on creating a seamless WordPress installation and configuration with Vagrant and a Linux virtual machine. It employs the use of scripts to automate the installation and configuration of a LAMP stack, installations of dependencies, and deploying of WordPress. It aims to solve the problem that developers face of quickly setting up a WordPress environment for testing and development.

Major features include:

A Vagrantfile to simplify the creation and management of VMs.

Automatic generation of all components of a LAMP server (Linux, Apache, MySQL, PHP).

Scripts for generating installations and configuration of WordPress.

Alterable to suit other devop needs.

commit.message:
Successfully set up Ubuntu VM with LAMP stack and deployed WordPress!

In this commit, I successfully set up a Virtual Machine (VM) running Ubuntu and installed a full LAMP stack to deploy WordPress. This project has significantly enhanced my understanding of web development and server management.

Here's a breakdown of what I accomplished:

1. Initialized a Vagrant box using the Ubuntu focal64 image, allowing me to create a consistent and isolated development environment.
2. Carefully configured the Vagrantfile to set up networking options and resource allocation, which was a great learning experience in VM customization.
3. Updated package lists and installed essential dependencies, including Apache, MySQL, and PHP. I ensured everything was up to date for optimal performance.
4. Created a directory structure for WordPress and set file permissions, which taught me the importance of security in web applications.
5. Configured Apache to host the WordPress site, enabling URL rewriting for clean URLs. This taught me how to manage virtual hosts effectively.
6. Established a dedicated MySQL database for WordPress, creating a user with tailored permissions to enhance security.
7. Generated unique authentication keys for the `wp-config.php` file, reinforcing the importance of securing sensitive information.
8. Completed the WordPress installation through the browser, which was incredibly satisfying as I saw my hard work come to life!

This setup not only serves as a robust foundation for developing and testing WordPress sites but also boosts my confidence in handling server configurations and deployments. I'm looking forward to building upon this project in future endeavors!

commit.message:
Remove vendor dir, simplify build & test tooling

"Libraries should never vendor their dependencies"
  https://peter.bourgon.org/go-best-practices-2016/#dependency-management
The only thing in there were test-support packages anyhow

Remove Godeps folder, nothing to manage!

Remove build.sh
- not much here to build now that we've split out plugins
   - for non-AMD64 platforms, travis just runs go build directly

Clean up test.sh
- no vendor --> simpler logic for enumerating packages
- use "bash strict mode"
   http://redsymbol.net/articles/unofficial-bash-strict-mode
- coveralls token not required for public repos

Simplify .travis.yml, update to work without vendor
- fewer env vars
- go get -t ./...

Clean up Vagrantfile
- no godep required anymore
- bump Golang version 1.9.2

chore: replace docker-compose V1 with docker compose V2

Compose V2 integrates compose functions into the Docker platform.
This integration includes the `compose` command as part of the Docker CLI.

You can run Compose V2 by replacing the hyphen (-) with a space,
using `docker compose`, instead of `docker-compose`.

As Docker Compose now comes bundled with Docker CLI, we don't have
to do anything special to install Docker Compose.

Compose V2 has been re-written in Go, which improves integration with
other Docker command-line features, and allows it to run natively on
macOS on Apple silicon, Windows, and Linux, without dependencies
such as Python.

See also https://docs.docker.com/compose/compose-v2/

In our case, this also fixes the problem related to container names.

With the [vagrant-docker-compose](https://github.com/leighmcculloch/vagrant-docker-compose)
plugin, that installed Docker Compose V1 into the VM, containers run
with `docker-compose up` at `vagrant up` used `_` as separator for the
container names.

Executing the `docker-compose up` by hand created containers that used
`-` as separator, which lead to a naming inconsistency, making it
difficult to document and automate container management.

Now the `Vagrantfile` does not use the `vagrant-docker-compose` plugin
to create containers at `vagrant up`. It directly executes the
`docker compose up` command (V2), so the container names now use `-` as
separator in all situations, eliminating this inconsistency.
